Look for whole fish that smell clean. Avoid bruised sardines-you want the best product when you make sardines. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5d/Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5d/Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Stay away from old fish. Aged sardines will have "belly burn," a condition where the guts start to come out of the fish. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d0/Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d0/Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-Sardines-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use the fillet knife to slice along each side of the backbone behind the ribs. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cut underneath the ribs of the fresh sardine and slice upward, away from the backbone. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/03/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/03/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use sharp scissors to snip the backbone where it connects to the head and where it meets the tail. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove the backbones with your thumb and forefinger before you cook sardines. Start at the tail and move your hand along the bone toward the head. As you move along the spine, lift the bone from the fish. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/69/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/69/Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-Sardines-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
